  , issueCommentBody =
      "Sure ! Just to be clear, it's not to \"compile\" but to install the driver to my maven repo (.m2) so I can use it in my other project.\r\n\r\nHere is my build.gradle:\r\n```groovy\r\napply plugin: 'java'\r\napply plugin: 'maven'\r\n\r\nversion = '0.5-b1'\r\ngroup = \"rethinkdb\"\r\narchivesBaseName = \"java-driver\"\r\n\r\n\r\nsourceCompatibility = 1.8\r\ntargetCompatibility = 1.8\r\n\r\n//create a single Jar with all dependencies baked in\r\ntask fatJar(type: Jar) {\r\n    archiveName = \"rethinkdb-\"+version+\".jar\"\r\n    from { configurations.compile.collect { it.isDirectory() ? it : zipTree(it) } }\r\n    with jar\r\n}\r\n\r\nrepositories {\r\n    mavenCentral()\r\n}\r\n\r\ndependencies {\r\n    testCompile \"junit:junit:4.12\"\r\n    compile 'org.slf4j:slf4j-api:1.7.2'\r\n    compile group: 'com.googlecode.json-simple', name: 'json-simple', version: '1.1.1'\r\n}\r\n\r\nbuildDir = '../../build/drivers/java/gradle'\r\n```\r\n\r\nI specifically added those 3 lines:\r\n```groovy\r\napply plugin: 'maven'\r\ngroup = \"rethinkdb\"\r\narchivesBaseName = \"java-driver\"\r\n```\r\nThen you can \"gradle clean install\" it to the local repo."
